<br/>

<br/>
To some extent, purchasing decisions should be driven by budget, but it is worth bearing in mind that any savings on the desktop computer itself can be put toward a good external display such as Apple's Studio Display, which starts from &#36;1,599. For example, an M4 Pro &zwnj;Mac mini&zwnj; paired with a Studio Display comes to &#36;2,898, which is just &#36;899 more than a lone base model &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj; and &#36;1,101 less than the &zwnj;M2&zwnj; Ultra &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj; with no display.
<br/>

<br/>
You should only consider the &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj; if you have a professional workflow that can leverage the extreme power of the &zwnj;M2&zwnj; Max or &zwnj;M2&zwnj; Ultra, as well as its additional ports and memory options. If you need the &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj;, you will likely know that you are looking for a highly powerful machine that is capable of supporting specific intense workflows. Most customers should choose the M4 Pro &zwnj;Mac mini&zwnj; over the &zwnj;M2&zwnj; Max &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj;, saving &#36;700 when looking at the base models. There will likely still be substantial savings when it comes to custom configurations.
<br/>

<br/>
The &zwnj;Mac mini&zwnj; is also a better choice for most users at the current time since its chip technology is two generations ahead of the &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj;, offering higher clock speeds, much faster single-core performance, a redesigned GPU architecture, AV1 decode, a markedly more powerful Neural Engine, and more. As a result, those looking to buy an &zwnj;M2&zwnj; Max &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj; may be better served by the M4 Pro &zwnj;Mac mini&zwnj;. Those who can take advantage of the performance of the &zwnj;M2&zwnj; Ultra &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj; may still be better off with that high-end machine.<div class=\"linkback\">Related Roundups: <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/mac-studio/\">Mac Studio</a>, <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/mac-mini/\">Mac mini</a></div><div class=\"linkback\">Tags: <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/m2/\">M2</a>, <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/m4-mac-mini/\">M4 Mac mini</a>, <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/m4-macs/\">M4 Macs</a></div><div class=\"linkback\">Buyer's Guide: <a href=\"https://buyersguide.macrumors.com/#Mac-Studio\">Mac Studio (Caution)</a>, <a href=\"https://buyersguide.macrumors.com/#Mac_Mini\">Mac Mini (Buy Now)</a></div><div class=\"linkback\">Related Forums: <a href=\"https://forums.macrumors.com/forums/mac-studio.237\">Mac Studio</a>, <a href=\"https://forums.macrumors.com/forums/mac-mini.146\">Mac mini</a></div><br/>This article, &quot;<a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/mac-mini-vs-mac-studio/\">Mac Mini vs. Mac Studio Buyer&#039;s Guide: 25+ Differences Compared</a>&quot; first appeared on <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com\">MacRumors.com</a><br/><br/><a href=\"https://forums.macrumors.com/threads/mac-mini-vs-mac-studio-buyers-guide-25-differences-compared.2337590/\">Discuss this article</a> in our forums<br/><br/>")) (item nil (title nil "Apple Expected to Unveil New MacBook Pros Today With These Features") (link nil "https://www.macrumors.com/2024/10/30/what-to-expect-from-m4-macbook-pros/") (comments nil "https://forums.macrumors.com/threads/apple-expected-to-unveil-new-macbook-pros-today-with-these-features.2441432/") (pubDate nil "Wed, 30 Oct 2024 06:45:00 PDT") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "https://www.macrumors.com/2024/10/30/what-to-expect-from-m4-macbook-pros/") (creator nil "Joe Rossignol") (category nil "MacBook Pro 14\" &amp; 16\"") (description nil "Apple <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2024/10/28/apple-promises-two-more-mac-announcements/\">promised three Mac-related product announcements this week</a>, and it has delivered on two of them so far with <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2024/10/28/apple-announces-imac-with-m4-chip-upgraded-camera-new-colors-and-more/\">the new iMac on Monday</a> and <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2024/10/29/apple-announces-redesigned-mac-mini/\">the redesigned Mac mini on Tuesday</a>. The final announcement today is expected to be updated 14-inch and 16-inch MacBook Pro models with M4, M4 Pro, and M4 Max chips.
