<br/>

<br/>
<img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/article-new/2024/10/M4-mini-Glowing-Yellow-and-Purple.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"2500\" height=\"1406\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-973634\" />
<br/>
There are now two desktop Macs and four Apple silicon chip options for users who do not need the expandability of the <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/mac-pro/\">Mac Pro</a>. The &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj; starts at $1,999, overshadowing the $599 starting price of the <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/m4-mac-mini/\">M4 Mac mini</a> and even the $1,399 starting price of the M4 Pro &zwnj;Mac mini&zwnj;, so do you need the performance of the &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj;, or is the humble &zwnj;Mac mini&zwnj; sufficient for your needs? Our guide helps to answer the question of how to decide which of these two desktop Macs is best for you.
<br/>

<br/>
The &zwnj;Mac mini&zwnj; and the &zwnj;Mac Studio&zwnj; share some fundamental features, including a familiar, boxy silver aluminum design, two front-facing USB-C ports along with HDMI and ethernet on the rear, and Apple silicon chipsets. That being said, the two machines have much more in contrast than they do in common, including different chip options, memory capacities, ports, and external display support capabilities.
